content.text:
Great question! Let me show you the pattern difference:

## Current Approach (Composables - Over-Complicated)

```typescript
// useAnimateElement.ts (335 lines)
import { useAnimation } from './useAnimation' // 2803 lines!

const { playAnimation } = useAnimateElement(element, 'fadeIn', { 
  duration: 300, 
  easing: 'ease-out' 
})
await playAnimation()
```

## Simplified Approach (CSS @keyframes)

### 1. Define Reusable @keyframes in CSS

```css
/* src/styles/animations.css */
@layer utilities {
  /* ============================================
   * KEYFRAME DEFINITIONS (Reusable animations)
   * ============================================ */

  @keyframes fade-in {
    from { opacity: 0; }
    to { opacity: 1; }
  }

  @keyframes slide-up {
    from {
      opacity: 0;
      transform: translateY(1rem);
    }
    to {
      opacity: 1;
      transform: translateY(0);
    }
  }

  @keyframes slide-down {
    from {
      opacity: 0;
      transform: translateY(-1rem);
    }
    to {
      opacity: 1;
      transform: translateY(0);
    }
  }

  @keyframes scale-in {
    from {
      opacity: 0;
      transform: scale(0.95);
    }
    to {
      opacity: 1;
      transform: scale(1);
    }
  }

  @keyframes pop-in {
    0% {
      opacity: 0;
      transform: scale(0.8);
    }
    50% {
      transform: scale(1.05);
    }
    100% {
      opacity: 1;
      transform: scale(1);
    }
  }

  @keyframes shake {
    0%, 100% { transform: translateX(0); }
    25% { transform: translateX(-0.5rem); }
    75% { transform: translateX(0.5rem); }
  }

  @keyframes pulse {
    0%, 100% { opacity: 1; }
    50% { opacity: 0.7; }
  }

  @keyframes spin {
    from { transform: rotate(0deg); }
    to { transform: rotate(360deg); }
  }

  /* ============================================
   * UTILITY CLASSES (Apply animations)
   * ============================================ */

  .animate-fade-in {
    animation: fade-in 300ms ease-out;
  }

  .animate-slide-up {
    animation: slide-up 300ms ease-out;
  }

  .animate-slide-down {
    animation: slide-down 300ms ease-out;
  }

  .animate-scale-in {
    animation: scale-in 300ms ease-out;
  }

  .animate-pop-in {
    animation: pop-in 400ms cubic-bezier(0.68, -0.55, 0.265, 1.55);
  }

  .animate-shake {
    animation: shake 400ms ease-in-out;
  }

  .animate-pulse {
    animation: pulse 2s ease-in-out infinite;
  }

  .animate-spin {
    animation: spin 1s linear infinite;
  }

  /* Duration variants */
  .animate-fast {
    animation-duration: 150ms;
  }

  .animate-slow {
    animation-duration: 500ms;
  }

  .animate-slower {
    animation-duration: 800ms;
  }

  /* Delay variants */
  .animate-delay-100 {
    animation-delay: 100ms;
  }

  .animate-delay-200 {
    animation-delay: 200ms;
  }

  .animate-delay-300 {
    animation-delay: 300ms;
  }
}
```

### 2. Use in Vue Components (No Composables!)

```vue
<template>
  <!-- Simple: Just add class -->
  <div class="animate-fade-in">
    Fades in automatically on mount
  </div>

  <!-- With delay -->
  <div class="animate-slide-up animate-delay-200">
    Slides up after 200ms
  </div>

  <!-- Conditional animation -->
  <div :class="{ 'animate-pop-in': isVisible }">
    Animates when isVisible becomes true
  </div>

  <!-- Loading spinner -->
  <div class="animate-spin">
    <Icon icon="mdi:loading" />
  </div>
</template>
```

### 3. Optional: Tiny Composable for Programmatic Control

If you NEED JavaScript control (rare), keep ONE simple composable:

```typescript
// src/composables/useAnimate.ts (~30 lines instead of 2803!)
import { ref, type Ref } from 'vue'

export function useAnimate(element: Ref<HTMLElement | null>) {
  const isAnimating = ref(false)

  const animate = (className: string, duration = 300) => {
    if (!element.value) return Promise.resolve()

    isAnimating.value = true
    element.value.classList.add(className)

    return new Promise<void>((resolve) => {
      setTimeout(() => {
        isAnimating.value = false
        resolve()
      }, duration)
    })
  }

  const stop = () => {
    if (!element.value) return
    element.value.getAnimations().forEach(anim => anim.cancel())
    isAnimating.value = false
  }

  return { animate, stop, isAnimating }
}

// Usage:
const el = ref<HTMLElement | null>(null)
const { animate } = useAnimate(el)

await animate('animate-fade-in', 300)
```

## Comparison

### Before (Your PR):
```vue
<script setup>
import { ref, onMounted } from 'vue'
import { useAnimateElement } from '@/components/vue/animations/composables/useAnimateElement'

const el = ref(null)
const { playAnimation } = useAnimateElement(el, 'fadeIn', { duration: 300 })

onMounted(() => {
  playAnimation()
})
</script>

<template>
  <div ref="el">Content</div>
</template>
```

### After (Simplified):
```vue
<script setup>
import { ref } from 'vue'
const isVisible = ref(false)
onMounted(() => isVisible.value = true)
</script>

<template>
  <div :class="{ 'animate-fade-in': isVisible }">
    Content
  </div>
</template>
```

**Even simpler for most cases:**
```vue
<template>
  <!-- No JS needed! -->
  <div class="animate-fade-in">
    Content
  </div>
</template>
```

## Benefits of @keyframes Approach

1. **Simpler**: CSS classes vs complex composables
2. **Performant**: Browser-native animations
3. **Maintainable**: 50 lines of CSS vs 3000+ lines of TS
4. **Reusable**: Same @keyframes everywhere
5. **Declarative**: HTML classes vs imperative JS
6. **SSR-safe**: No client-side JS required

## When You MIGHT Need a Composable

- Chaining multiple animations in sequence
- Responding to animation end events
- Dynamic animation parameters from API

But 95% of animations = just CSS classes!

---

**Does this make sense? Should I implement this simplified approach?**

